description.narrative:
The annual reporting presents how the programme was implemented in the fourth programme year, from 1 October 2019 until 1 October 2020. The report is submitted on time and with adequate quality. The programme progress remains as planned.
BOS submits the annual reporting in line with the Agreement, namely as per Agreement Article 5.2 and it is narrative report with the annual work plan and budget for the forthcoming year while the annual audited financial report is submitted as per Agreement Article 5.3. The deadline for submission of the annual audited report was requested duly due to corona circumstances, and approved by the Embassy (mail 2 Nov 2020).
The Annual Report follows the format of and the activities envisaged by the Project Document (Annex I to the Grant Agreement).
The Annual Narrative Report consists of:
- Report on implementation of the project activities with description of activities performed during the reporting period of the Fourth Programme year;
-CS4EU Programme objectives and achieved results with a review of achieved outputs compared to planned outputs and achieved outcomes compared to plan and progress towards achieving the longer-term objectives;
- Lessons learned during the Fourth Programme year of implementation;
- Annexes and supporting documents (reports of programme partners, more detailed reports on held workshops and similar).
The programme in the reporting period provided support to 11 partner organizations aiming to enable civil society partners and media representatives to approach strategically and more effectively to advocacy topics. The11 supported organisations and media during fourth programme year received programme support for implementation of their envisaged activities and goals in line with organisations’ strategy and mission in current programme year.
In the fourth programme year, following clusters are made of 11 projects, in line with thematic priorities of the programme:
Rule of law and human rights protection
Mental Disability Rights Initiative MDRI-S;
Human Rights committee Valjevo;
Association of Public Prosecutors and Deputy Public Prosecutors of Serbia;
Uzice Child Rights Centre;ENECA Nis.
Media reporting and freedom of information protection
Independent Journalists’ Association of Serbia;
Center for Investigative Journalism – Foundation (CINS);
European Western Balkans;
Crime and Corruption Reporting Network – KRIK;
NGO Women’s Forum Prijepolje – TV Forum.
Youth policy and youth participation in decision-making
National Youth Council of Serbia (KOMS).
In accordance with specific needs and capacities of participating partner organizations, BOS team engaged in provision of tailor-made expert support to each organization. Taking into account the specificity of the each of the partner organizations selected to receive Programme support, BOS team used the individual approach as the most efficient way of the support under the Programme. Such an approach proved that, despite limited capacities of civil society organizations, the targeted, needs-based and tailor-made expert support could bring significant improvements to the way organizations implement, monitor and evaluate their own projects in order to resolve challenges in their local communities in the long term. The BOS assessment is that this approach supports good results such as that some of the partners adopted their own internal acts which regulate the areas of transparency and anticorruption, environmental protection and sustainable development and gender equality. The BOS team intends to continue with the further intensive application of the individual mentoring approach in order to further strengthen the internal capacities of the programme partner organizations.
In the fourth year of the Programme, BOS team introduced the Media Peer learning programme as an innovative capacity building model, with an aim to support mutual exchange, learning from each other and launching the joint initiatives, which would multiply the potential for the broadest possible communication and outreach impact and effect of the media partners’ initiatives.
In addition to individual successes of partner organizations supported within the programme, its contribution in connecting, enabling exchange, mutual learning and support was recognized by participating organizations as one of the key values of the programme.
During this Programme year new component “Building strategic partnership between the CSOs and business sector” was introduced and already brought some very good signs of progress such as:
- Comparative analysis “The role of civil and business sector in the accession process of Serbia to the European Union and cooperation possibilities” conducted and published;
- More than 30 individual meetings organized, which resulted in the improvement of the cooperation with representatives of the business sector; 
- First networking event “Innovation- Integration” on cooperation between business and civil sector organized;
- Work plan and activity plan created in order to improve cooperation between civil and business sector; 
- Online campaign created and conducted in order to inform and raise public awareness on this topic;
- Strategic cooperation with OTP Bank within „New Ideas Generator “initiative established.
BOS intends to engage in the coming programme period more actively with the civil society organizations in order to concretize topics that would be potentially achievable through cooperation with the business sector.
The Civil Society Transformer platform, during the Fourth Programme Year, have continued to serve as a central information hub and main tool for communication between Programme partners. It has been continuously developed, improved and updated throughout the Programme implementation period. Besides, serving as an information hub and communication tool, one of the platform’s goals is to ensure transparency and increase visibility of all partners’ and Programme activities. During the reporting period, BOS reports that it has been published more than 80 articles on Programme’s and partners’ activities, around 65 calls for project funding, and it was connected to the web-portal “Let’s Talk About Negotiations”, which is dealing with EU related topics.
BOS was actively engaged in building internal capacities of the Programme partners for the advanced use of the online tools during the Covid-19 outbreak and support the programme implementing partners to work in the new circumstances. BOS also redefined and set-up work plan for its planned activities and especially annual networking event. BOS organized and realised the second networking event within the Regional Annual Conference Move.Link.Engage: “Development for Real: Partnership, Solidarity and Responsibility in post COVID 19 Era” in the period 21st – 23rd September 2020. with some 70 participants and prominent speakers and panelists, and concluded that solidarity and cross-sectoral partnership are of key importance in overcoming the economic consequences of the pandemic both in Serbia and in the Western Balkans region. The pandemic has particularly affected the economy, but the adaptability of national governments and public sector was inevitable, as well as transformation of private and civil sectors.
The corona virus outbreak has required and will require constant adaptation to new mechanisms and tools for work. Therefore, the BOS team plans provide all the continious necessary support to the partners through various related activities: trainings, workshops, individual consultations in order to smooth the implementation of the project during upcoming programme period.
BOS is committed to further engage with the same programme partners, to strengthen the sustainability perspective. BOS assesses that th partners' are not so much activity driven, but more missions driven which highly contributes to quality of their work and in increasing of their impact and ownership of achieved results in their local communities. 
Gender ratio of participants in all Programme partners’ activities is 55% female and 45% male. Although these numbers show more active participation of women than men in the implementation of project activities, careful analysis of these data indicate that this might be due to thematic focus of activities of two programme partners – Uzice Centre for Child Rights and Independent Journalists’ Association of Serbia. BOS therefore concludes and reports that participation of women in decision making process is still at low level, and needs to be more developed and enhanced through better and structured practices and advocacy in Serbian gender policy framework.
One lesson learnt that BOS reports is needed alliances and strategic partnership between media projects and civil society, having in mind the importance of visibility of topics related to EU accession process. BOS considers that this will also help in bringing topics closer to citizens not as topics of high politics but as topics that will help in improving their lives in local communities.  
BOS team continues to implement comprehensive anti-corruption measures in its work with programme partners ad also together with them since the programme aims to contribute to anticorruption policy in Serbia; BOS and all programme partners directly or indirectly contribute to the advocacy for improvement of the rule of law in Serbia and transparency and anticorruption policy and its implementation. Two media partners KRIK and CINS are leading in investigative journalism focused reporting on corruption cases. They work and evidence about potential corruption cases serves as excellent starting point further policy and legal research and advocacy for changes in relation to Chapters 23 and 24. BOS remains recognised and invited by other programmes and projects related to the issues of transparency and anticorruption, such as by the Coalition for Oversight of Public Finances, UNDP and others.
Overall, the programme continues with good potential to deliver results.
